@node Short "Short description of this doc"
@prev Share

    @{b}@{fg highlight}If you don't like these docs...@{fg text}@{ub}

    This  program is very simple if you know exactly what's up and what's it
for.  I say you must @{b}read precisely@{ub} all document, better in as order as it's
in the contents.  That lets you know everything you need.
    If Polyglot interests you (remember, it's not for lazy people!), install
it, run and keep the directions!

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Navigating in the documentation@{fg text}@{ub}

    As  you've discovered it's a normal @{b}AmigaGuide@{ub} doc.  I hope everyone can
use  it.   The  @{b}@{fg fill}Contents@{ub}@{fg text}  button  lets  you  move to a "parent" page for the
current  (that is the local or global contents), @{b}@{fg fill}Retrace@{ub}@{fg text} returns to the last
visited  page.   Using  @{b}@{fg fill}Browse <@{ub}@{fg text} and @{b}@{fg fill}>@{ub}@{fg text} you can go to the prev/next node in a
group.   If  you  want a quick alphabetical index of most important things -
just click on @{b}@{fg fill}Index@{ub}@{fg text}.
    The  titles  and  subtitles  are @{b}@{fg highlight}highlighted@{ub}@{fg text}.  Most important things are
printed  @{b}bold@{ub}.   Less  important  notes and some links are @{i}italic@{ui}.  Names of
files, gadgets, keys and examples are @{b}@{fg fill}coloured@{ub}@{fg text}.

    @{b}@{fg highlight}About translation@{fg text}@{ub}

    This  is  an  @{b}English@{ub} version of doc (did you know it?), I hope you will
know  what  I mean here :-).  Yes, I didn't learn English too much lately...
There's  also  a  @{b}Polish@{ub}  version  available  for  my  compatriots.  Look at
@{" locale " link Local} for more international info.  (Perhaps you might do it better.)

@endnode


@node Requi "What does the program need?"

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Requirements@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{b}Operating  system:@{ub}   Minimum  is  2.05 (V37), for AGA-palette and better
gadgets layout I recommend 3.0 (V39).

    @{b}Processor:@{ub}  I think every MC680x0, nice speed from 020.

    @{b}Memory:@{ub}   Minimum  is 1MB without Workbench running, on 2MB you can work
with no restrictions.  See also @{" memory management " link Memor}.

    @{b}Hard disk:@{ub}  Not necessary, but recommended.  See @{" disk operations " link LoSav}.

    @{b}Additional  libraries:@{ub}  Polyglot uses the @{" reqtools.library " link Copyr} V38+, which
is  @{" installed " link Insta}  by  the  installation script.  It needs locale.library only
if you use other language than English.

    @{b}Others:@{ub}   With  the  standard fonts you may easily use most European and
American   languages.   For  Polish  version  a  Polish  font  (AmigaPL)  is
requested.

@endnode

@node InsRu "What to do to work"
@next Basic

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Installation and running@{fg text}@{ub}
@{i}
    Remember  that  you  have to install and run the program correctly for a
normal  work.  There are important icon tooltypes which should be set if you
don't use the installer script or change place of the program.
@{ui}
    @{" Installation of Polyglot " link Insta}
    @{" Running first time       " link FirRu}
    @{" Start from Workbench     " link RunWb}
    @{" Start from Shell/CLI     " link RunSh}

@endnode

@node Insta "With Installer or manually"
@prev Insta
@toc InsRu

    @{b}@{fg highlight}The Installer script@{fg text}@{ub}

    You can use the @{b}installer script@{ub} if you wish to install the program on a
hard  disk  (or  a floppy).  You need the @{" Installer " link Copyr} program on your system
disk,  it  is distributed with the Workbench package for HD-users since V2.0
or in PD-packages, CD-ROMs etc.
    If  you  run  it, it will copy all necessary files in directed place and
also  set  the  @{b}paths@{ub}  in  @{" tooltypes " link RunWb}.   You  have to do it yourself if you
install it manually.

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Manual installation@{fg text}@{ub}

    You  can  just  copy  @{b}all@{ub}  the Polyglot @{b}directory@{ub} (after unpacking it if
needed)  best in Workbench by drag&drop its icon into any place on a disk or
harddisk.  You needn't change anything then.  Then copy the @{b}reqtools.library@{ub}
to your system @{b}libs:@{ub}  directory (if you haven't got one).
    If  you  wish  to  use  the  @{b}English  version@{ub},  just  delete  the Polish
documentation,  locale  and  of course the installer script.  Else, you will
have  to  leave the @{b}catalogs@{ub} dir or just put it into your locale:  directory
and  set the @{b}@{fg fill}LANGUAGE@{ub}@{fg text} parameter in @{" icon " link RunWb}.  (Locale.library is needed then).
As I wrote, only Polish locales are available now.

    You  will have to use a @{b}specific font@{ub} only for such languages which have
special  national  characters.  The standard Ascii fonts are enough for most
European (except eastern) and American languages.

@endnode

@node FirRu "Saving the preferences"
@toc InsRu

    @{b}@{fg highlight}First time running@{fg text}@{ub}

    If you have installed the program correctly it's now ready to work.  You
should  @{b}set  it  up@{ub}  on  the beginning.  Preferences file isn't installed at
once,  because  it must be adjusted to your monitor, screen resolution, font
type etc.
    To do this, just run Polyglot from @{b}Workbench@{ub}.  It will automatically use
such  font  and  screen mode as Workbench (which are set with Prefs programs
for  Workbench).   You  may  modify  the settings and @{b}save@{ub} on your disk (see
@{" preferences " link Prefs}).

@endnode

@node RunWb "Start from an icon"
@toc InsRu

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Running from Workbench@{fg text}@{ub}

    Polyglot may be run in any way.  The simplest is from Workbench - by its
@{b}icon@{ub}.  If a data @{b}base@{ub} has an own icon (default it has), doubleclicking on it
runs Polyglot too and makes it @{b}load@{ub} the base immediately.

    In  the  program's  icon  there  are some @{b}paths@{ub} and @{b}file names@{ub} stored as
tooltypes.   They're  set  automatically during the @{b}installation@{ub} and you may
change  them  if  you  e.g.  move  the  program  into different directory of
change file names.  @{b}It's important!@{ub}
    The parameters have to be written into @{b}Tooltypes@{ub}:
    @{b}@{fg fill}PREFS@{ub}@{fg text} - name of preferences file (default is polyglot.prefs)
    @{b}@{fg fill}DIR@{ub}@{fg text}   - name of default bases directory (def. Bases)
    @{b}@{fg fill}ICON@{ub}@{fg text}  - name of icon saved with a base (without  .info  extension!).  If
            you   don't   give   it,   the  icon  is  not  written.  In  the
            DefaultTool  field  of  this  icon  should  be the full path for
            Polyglot.
    @{b}@{fg fill}LANGUAGE@{ub}@{fg text} - a  locale  language  that  should  be  used.  If  not given -
            Polyglot will use the default language set with the Locale prefs
            program. If the catalog couldn't be loaded, the built-in English
            language is used.

    In  first  three  arguments  you  needn't use full paths or the @{b}PROGDIR:@{ub}
assign,  because  all  names  are  corresponding  to  the  @{b}home directory@{ub} of
Polyglot (or current dir when running from Shell).
    As a language just enter its name - like english or polski.
@{i}
    See also: using the @{" appicon " link Appic} and @{" save/load " link LoSav} operations.
@{ui}
@endnode

@node RunSh "Shell or a start-up script"
@next RunSh
@toc InsRu

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Running from Shell/CLI@{fg text}@{ub}

    From  the @{b}Shell/CLI@{ub} Polyglot has to be run just by entering its path and
name.   You  can  also  add the name of @{b}base@{ub} which has to be loaded on start
(you needn't add the .plg extension).

    Additional  options are read from the @{" icon " link RunWb} (so the program @{b}should have
it@{ub} even if is started from Shell).  You may avoid them by entering your own.

    Here is the @{b}arguments template@{ub}:
@{b}@{fg fill}[<base[.plg]>] [PREFS=<prefs file>] [DIR=<bases dir>] [ICON=<bases icon>]
[LANGUAGE=<used language>]@{ub}@{fg text}

    The meaning of last four is same as in the @{" icon " link RunWb}.  These args you don't
enter are read from icon if it exists.

    The  @{b}default  directory@{ub} of Polyglot, to which all other paths are linked
is  the  @{b}current@{ub} directory of Shell.  That's why you should enter @{b}full paths@{ub}
in  icon  (installer  does  it)  or  arguments  if you are not in Polyglot's
directory.

    If you run the program from a @{b}script@{ub} (e.g.  startup-sequence),  remember
that you should write:
    @{b}@{fg fill}CD <directory of Polyglot>
    Run >NIL: Polyglot <other args>@{ub}@{fg text}
    The  program  doesn't  create its own process and you should start it by
@{b}Run@{ub} if you don't want the script to break.

@endnode


@node Basic "Basic concepts used in the program"
@prev InsRu

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Base, group, record@{fg text}@{ub}

    A  single  file  which  contain some data is a @{b}base@{ub}.  Its a parent unit,
like  a  directory, and has its own name, author, languages and description.
A base is treated entirely only during saving and loading it from the disk.
    The  main  unit  is  a  @{b}group@{ub}.   There may be up to 16 group, completely
@{b}independent@{ub}.   Each group has its own name and a description and it may have
different  properties  (except names of author and languages).  You can work
with only one group at once (but all are in memory).
    Each  group may include up to 256 @{b}records@{ub}.  Each record is like a single
item in test (group).  And each record has a specific @{b}form@{ub}, it's only filled
by different words, sentences etc.

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Types of tests@{fg text}@{ub}
@{i}
    Tests  (that  means  groups  with  its records) may have different form,
depending  on  its  @{" application " link Pract}.   More informations about tests types and
configuration  of  them  are  in the chapter about @{" creating groups " link GrTyp}.
@{ui}
@endnode

@remark #################################################################


@node Using "Basics of using the program"
@next MainM

    @{b}@{fg highlight}How to use Polyglot?@{fg text}@{ub}
@{i}
    The  @{b}user interface@{ub} of the program is entirely system-friendly (gadtools
only)  and very simple but quite attractive (however it doesn't "blind" your
eyes).   The program uses its own screen, windows and requesters (reqtools).
Almost in 100% may be controlled by @{b}keyboard@{ub}.
    If you want to understand it earlier, you may @{" run " link InsRu} it now.
@{ui}
    @{" Screen and windows         " link ScrWi}
    @{" Gadgets and keyboard       " link Inter}
    @{" National chars on keyboard " link Chars}

@endnode

@node ScrWi "Windows to the world"
@prev ScrWi
@toc Using

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Screen and windows@{fg text}@{ub}

    Polyglot always opens its @{b}own screen@{ub}.  You may set its parameters freely
-  see  @{" preferences " link Prefs} for details.  If your screen cannot be open or there's
no  @{b}prefs  file@{ub}  (see @{" first running " link FirRu} of program), then the program tries to
use @{b}default mode@{ub} (like Workbench).  It's similar for the font etc.
    In OS3.0 or higher, the screen has a New Look (not a washing powder :-).
On the title bar it's displayed the amount of @{b}free@{ub} chip and fast @{b}memory@{ub} (see
@{" memory  management " link Memor})  if  any  window  is  activated, and also the name and
version of the program.

    Every  @{b}window@{ub}  is  opened  in the middle of screen, under its title bar.
Its  size  depends  on the font size.  Its fully @{b}scaled@{ub} (except the checkbox
gadgets under 2.x systems), but you can't change the size during work.

    The  program  opens  @{b}two@{ub}  windows  at  the most, and only one of them is
activated.   The  requesters deactivate both windows.  In an @{b}inactive window@{ub}
the  mouse  pointer  changes  into  a "clock" and either gadgets or keyboard
doesn't work.  It works good even under OS2.0!

@endnode

@node Inter "How does it work..."
@toc Using

    @{b}@{fg highlight}User interface, keyboard@{fg text}@{ub}

    Polyglot uses only system libraries - gadtools and reqtools, so the user
interface is @{b}clear@{ub} and @{b}comfortable@{ub}.  You may read in @{" preferences " link Prefs} about the
colour set.  The program has no pull-down menu because of not many functions
and easy keyboard support.
    All buttons are serviced with @{b}mouse@{ub} (by gadtools), in addition they have
a  program  @{b}keyboard@{ub}-service.  The  gadgets  are  also grouped with bevelled
boxes which helps you in orientation.

    Normal  @{b}buttons@{ub}  are  chosen  by  pressing  a key with @{u}underlined@{uu} letter
(without  any  shifts  etc.).  If the text is @{b}bold@{ub} (most frequently the @{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text}
gadget),  it  may be chosen by pressing @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}.  (In requesters too.) Many of
them  open  other  windows  or requesters - they haven't standard three dots
('...') because of no space.

    The  @{b}checkbox@{ub}  gadgets inverts when a shortcut is pressed (an underlined
letter  on  the  left).   @{b}Cycles@{ub} and @{b}sliders@{ub} works in similar way, These two
also understand the @{b}@{fg fill}Shift@{ub}@{fg text} key, which makes them go back.  The only exception
is  the slider in @{b}editor@{ub} window, which has to be used by the @{b}cursor@{ub} keys (@{b}@{fg fill}<-@{ub}@{fg text}
and @{b}@{fg fill}->@{ub}@{fg text}), with @{b}@{fg fill}Shift@{ub}@{fg text} it jumps five positions (see @{" editing " link Edito}).

    @{b}String@{ub}  gadgets  are  @{b}activated@{ub}  after pressing their shortcut, when the
edition  is done (you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}), next gadget is activated (like with @{b}@{fg fill}TAB@{ub}@{fg text})
if  it's  necessary  (in  fact  it's  very  intuitive but the description is
complicated  :^).  In preferences window the text gadgets has also shortcuts
to corresponding @{b}@{fg fill}[?]@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}popup@{ub} gadgets.

    The  @{b}list@{ub}  in  main menu is simple to use - just with @{b}cursor@{ub} up and down
keys, also with @{b}@{fg fill}Shift@{ub}@{fg text}).  The "description lists" are described @{" here " link Descr}.
@{i}
    It  sounds  more  complicated  than it really is.  Just run the program,
load a base and work with it - you will learn it quickly.
@{ui}
@endnode

@node Chars "Keyboard and national keys"
@next Chars
@toc Using

    @{b}@{fg highlight}National keys@{fg text}@{ub}

    This  text  is dedicated mostly to my compatriots, which have to use @{b}own
keyboards@{ub}  including those strange Polish letters :-) But if you want to use
characters  different than the standard 26 Latin letters, you will find this
text @{b}useful@{ub}.
    There  are  two  standard  Amiga  @{b}keyboards@{ub}  - English (or American) and
German.  In both, you may use the @{b}foreign keys@{ub} by pressing:
    @{b}@{fg fill}ALT+f, aeiou -> ŕčěňů
    ALT+g, aeio  -> áéíó
    ALT+j, ano   -> ăńő
    ALT+k, aouy  -> äöü˙@{ub}@{fg text}
    E.g.  for  German  @{b}@{fg fill}ä@{ub}@{fg text},  you should press @{b}@{fg fill}ALT+k@{ub}@{fg text} and then @{b}@{fg fill}a@{ub}@{fg text}.  Big @{b}@{fg fill}Ä@{ub}@{fg text} is just
the  same  -  @{b}@{fg fill}ALT+k@{ub}@{fg text}  and  @{b}@{fg fill}A@{ub}@{fg text}.   Of  course  German keyboard has these letters
included.  Others are:
    @{b}@{fg fill}ALT+- = ß
    ALT+q = ĺ  ALT+Q = Ĺ
    ALT+d = đ  ALT+D = Đ
    ALT+; = ř  ALT+: = Ř@{ub}@{fg text} -- On German - @{b}@{fg fill}ALT+ö
    ALT+, = ć  ALT+< = Ć@{ub}@{fg text} \\_ Not available on
    @{b}@{fg fill}ALT+. = ç  ALT+> = Ç@{ub}@{fg text} /  German keyboard

    You  can find more informations with the system @{b}@{fg fill}KeyShow@{ub}@{fg text} program.  I just
included those infos here to make life easier :-)

@endnode

@remark #############################################################


@node MainM "Main menu"
@prev Inter
@next BasOp
@{i}
    You  may  run  Polyglot now and get to know it in practice while reading
this documentation.  The diagrams as below reflect program windows.  They're
not ideal (uneven because of the buttons), but let you use the documentation
like the program.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Main menu@{fg text}@{ub}

    +---------------------------------------------+     @{" GrSel: " link Descr}
    | Polyglot 1.2                                |  +---------+-+
    +---------------------------------------------+  |         |#|
    +---------------------------------------------+  |         |#|
    @{"  Load  " link LoadB}   File: [____________________________]  |         | |
    @{"  Save  " link SaveB}   Base: [____________________________]  |         |A|
    @{" Create " link BasCr} Author: [____________________________]  |         |V|
    @{" Change " link BasCh}  Lang.: [____________________________]  +---------+-+
    @{"  Info  " link BasIn}  @{"   Learn   " link LeTst}  @{"  Test   " link LeTst}  @{"   Edit   " link Edito}  @{" Add  " link GrpCr} [Del.]
    @{"  Quit  " link Main}  [About pr.]  [Iconify ]  @{"  Prefs   " link Prefs}  @{" Chng " link GrpCh} @{" Info " link GrpIn}

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Basic options@{fg text}@{ub}

@{b}the Polyglot logo@{ub} - a picture with program name, version and author.

@{b}Status@{ub} - below the logo, displays information about last operation or error.
In  case  of  error,  under OS3.x it is highlighted (white).  If you set the
@{" beeping  screen " link Beepi} to true it also makes a display beep (and probably a sound
effect).

@{b}Quit@{ub} - the program will ask if you're sure and let you save a changed base.

@{b}About  program@{ub} - a short information about the program, author and shareware
registration.

@{b}Iconify@{ub}  -  if  an @{" appicon " link Appic} is created, the screen with its windows will be
closed  but  the  base  still  remains in memory.  To call back the program,
doubleclick on appicon.

@endnode

@node GrSel "Group selection"
@prev GrSel
@next GrSel
@toc MainM

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Group selection@{fg text}@{ub}

    Selection  of  group which you're working with is possible only from the
@{" main  menu " link MainM}.   A  @{b}list  of  available groups@{ub} (max.  16) is displayed on the
right of main window.  You may select it with @{b}mouse@{ub} or @{b}cursor@{ub} keys ^ and v.
    Groups  in the list are displayed in their real order.  The @{b}name@{ub} of each
group  is  shown.   On the left, there may be an asterisk @{b}@{fg fill}*@{ub}@{fg text} showing that the
group is @{b}empty@{ub} (has no records).

@endnode

@remark ################################################################


@node BasOp "Base operations"
@prev MainM
@next GrpOp
@{i}
    I repeat - a base is a main unit which is saved into one file and stored
in  memory.   Is has its own name, languages, author and description.  There
are groups in a base.  See basic @{" concepts " link Basic} again.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Base operations window@{fg text}@{ub}

      Name: [______________]       @{" Base descr.: " link Descr}
    Author: [______________]  +-------------------+-+
    Lang.1: [______________]  |                   |#|
    Lang.2: [______________]  |                   |#|
    Num of grps/recs: [____]  +-------------------+-+
    [  Okay  ]  @{"   Cancel   " link MainM}  [___________][Add][Del]

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Modes of work@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{" Creating new base        " link BasCr}
    @{" Changing information     " link BasCh}
    @{" Displaying information   " link BasIn}

    @{" Base & group description " link Descr}

@endnode

@node BasCr "We begin..."
@prev BasCr
@toc BasOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Creating a new base@{fg text}@{ub}

    You  can  create a completely @{b}new@{ub} @{" base " link Basic} in this @{" window " link BasOp}.  If you have
changed an existing base first, the program asks you if you want to save it.
    You  have to enter a @{b}name@{ub} of the base (internal, independent of the file
name)  and  names  of @{b}two languages@{ub}.  First is the question language (except
the  simple  phrases  test where you can choose the language).  The other is
the  language  you're  learning.   If you don't enter something, the program
will tell it.
    You  may  also enter information about the @{b}author@{ub} and an additional base
@{b}description@{ub}.  See information about description @{" pattern " link Style} and @{" creating " link Descr}.

    If everything's all right, you can confirm (@{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text}) or @{b}@{fg fill}Cancel@{ub}@{fg text} changes.

@endnode

@node BasCh "Changing base information"
@toc BasOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Changing the information@{fg text}@{ub}

    In  any  moment you can @{b}change names@{ub} and @{" description " link Descr} of the base.  The
@{b}current data@{ub} will be displayed in the @{" window " link BasOp} in this mode.
    Press  @{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text}  after making changes (the program will check if you haven't
deleted  the  names  of  base  and  languages) or @{b}@{fg fill}Cancel@{ub}@{fg text} to restore previous
state.

@endnode

@node BasIn "Information"
@toc BasOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Information about base@{fg text}@{ub}

    You  @{b}can't  change@{ub} anything in the @{" window " link BasOp} in this mode.  The number or
@{b}groups@{ub}  and  @{b}records@{ub}  in  this  base  is  displayed  beside  the  names  and
description.   You  may  scroll the @{b}description@{ub} using ^ and v cursor keys or
with the slider.  Clicking @{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text} won't change anything.

@endnode

@node Descr "Describing list"
@next Descr
@toc BasOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Base and group description@{fg text}@{ub}

    A  @{b}description@{ub}  is  built  of  a number of @{b}lines@{ub}.  Each line is up to 32
characters  long,  all  description  is up to 512 chars long (longer will be
cut).   It may include some @{b}information@{ub} about the contents of group or base,
its  construction  and application etc.  The example @{b}pattern@{ub} of descriptions
is @{" here " link Style}.

    A  description  is serviced by seven gadgets.  The @{b}listview@{ub} displays all
lines  of  description.  It may be scrolled by the @{b}scroller@{ub} and arrows.  You
can use @{b}mouse@{ub} or @{b}@{fg fill}^@{ub}@{fg text} and @{b}@{fg fill}v@{ub}@{fg text} cursor keys to select lines from the list.
    Below there is a @{b}string@{ub} editing gadget and two buttons - @{b}@{fg fill}Add@{ub}@{fg text} and @{b}@{fg fill}Delete@{ub}@{fg text}.
Press  @{b}@{fg fill}Add@{ub}@{fg text}  to  add  a  @{b}new line@{ub} after the current one, then enter the line.
When you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}, the new line will be displayed in the list.  Press @{b}@{fg fill}Del@{ub}@{fg text}
to @{b}delete@{ub} the current selected line.
    You can use the shortcuts:  @{b}@{fg fill}a@{ub}@{fg text} - add a line, @{b}@{fg fill}d@{ub}@{fg text} - delete a line, @{b}@{fg fill}s@{ub}@{fg text} - begin
editing  current selected line.  If you select a line with mouse, the string
gadget  will  be  @{b}activated@{ub}  automatically.  If you use keyboard you have to
activate it with the @{b}@{fg fill}s@{ub}@{fg text} key (or mouse).

@endnode

@remark #################################################################


@node GrpOp "Group operations"
@prev BasOp
@next LoSav
@{i}
    Groups exist independently in the base.  The decide about record's form.
See - basic @{" concepts " link Basic}, @{" configuration " link GrTyp} of groups and @{" practical " link Pract} infos.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Group operations window@{fg text}@{ub}

    Name: [__________________]         @{" Group descr.: " link Descr}
    Type: [@|________________]       +---------------+-+
    F: [ ] [____]  Cols: [##__] [_]  |               |#|
    G: [ ] [____]  Rows: [#___] [_]  |               |#|
    H: [ ] [____] Grp. [__] Rec [_]  +---------------+-+
       [  Okay  ]  @{"   Cancel   " link MainM}      [_______][Add][Del]

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Modes of work@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{" Creating a group  " link GrpCr}
    @{" Changing a group  " link GrpCh}
    @{" Information       " link GrpIn}

    @{" Group description " link Descr}

@endnode

@node GrpCr "A new group"
@prev GrpCr
@toc GrpOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Creating a new group@{fg text}@{ub}

    A  @{b}new  group@{ub}  is  added  after  the current one.  You have to enter its
@{b}name@{ub}  and  (if  you  want)  a  @{b}description@{ub} (see  @{" pattern " link Style} and @{" creating " link Descr} a
description) in its @{" window " link GrpOp}.

    You  may  select the @{b}type@{ub} (cycle button), @{b}flags@{ub} and @{b}size@{ub} of group.  More
information  about  group  types  and  configuration  are @{" here " link GrTyp}, see also -
@{" practice " link Pract} with groups.

@endnode

@node GrpCh "Changing"
@toc GrpOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Group changing@{fg text}@{ub}

    If  you call the @{" window " link GrpOp} from @{" main menu " link MainM} you can change @{b}only name@{ub} and
description  of a group (unless the group is empty).  The @{b}other settings@{ub} are
available  @{b}only@{ub}  from @{" editor " link Edito} window.  You may confirm of cancel changes to
leave the window.

    If   you   change  such  parameters  as  special  @{b}flags@{ub}  and  @{b}size@{ub}  (see
@{" group types " link GrTyp})  from  the  @{b}editor@{ub},  there  are  often  some  data @{b}deleted@{ub} or
@{b}modified@{ub}.  You'll be informed about it and you may cancel the changes anyway
or confirm them.

    You  @{b}can  not  change@{ub}  the @{b}type@{ub} of group (unless it's empty) and @{b}size@{ub} of
editing test with same questions and normal choose test.  Else the change is
possible,  but  may  delete something (see above).  The @{b}main flags@{ub} cannot be
changed too.  Well, that means you may click on the tick, but it will return
to  previous  position.   You may also move the slider, but the number won't
change, so why should you do it?

@endnode

@node GrpIn "Info about group"
@next GrpIn
@toc GrpOp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Information@{fg text}@{ub}

    You  @{b}can't  change@{ub}  anything in the @{" window " link GrpOp} in this mode.  You can only
look  at the @{b}info@{ub}.  The checkboxes and sliders are not disabled to make them
well visible.  You may move them, but their real position won't change.

@endnode

@remark ###############################################################


@node LoSav "Disk operations"
@prev GrpOp
@next Prefs
@{i}
    The  whole  base  is always saved or loaded, if it includes any records.
See also @{" errors " link Error} on disk operations.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Loading and saving the base@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{" Loading base        " link LoadB}
    @{" Appicon and restart " link Appic}
    @{" Saving base         " link SaveB}

@endnode

@node LoadB "Loading a base"
@prev LoadB
@toc LoSav

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Loading@{fg text}@{ub}

    If  you  have  been working with a @{b}base@{ub} and @{b}changed@{ub} it, the program will
ask  you if you want to save it (see @{" saving " link SaveB}).  Then, a @{b}file requester@{ub} will
open  (reqtools).   You  may  select  a file to load.  It must have a '@{b}@{fg fill}.plg@{ub}@{fg text}'
@{b}extension@{ub}.   If  you  won't  give  it,  it will be @{b}added@{ub} automatically.  The
default  @{b}directory@{ub}  for loading bases may be set with the @{b}@{fg fill}DIR@{ub}@{fg text} tooltype - see
@{" icon " link RunWb}.

    First,  the  program @{b}checks@{ub} if the file exists and is a correct Polyglot
base  -  else  you  will be warned.  The old base (if there was any) will be
@{b}deleted@{ub} from memory and the program will @{b}load@{ub} the selected one.

    Sometimes,  if  there was an error during saving or the file is damaged,
the  base  may be @{b}incomplete@{ub}.  The program will tell you, that the base will
be  loaded @{b}partly@{ub}.  If a @{b}lack of memory@{ub} occurs during loading, the base will
be loaded partly too.  Look @{" here " link ErLoa} for more infos about errors.

@endnode

@node Appic "Loading by appicon"
@toc LoSav

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Appicon and starting again@{fg text}@{ub}

    Polyglot  creates  an  @{b}appicon@{ub} on the Workbench screen, it looks exactly
like  its  own @{" icon " link RunWb}. It works even under @{" Shell/CLI " link RunSh} if @{b}Workbench@{ub} is open
and Polyglot has an icon.
    if  you  @{b}doubleclick@{ub} the appicon, the Polyglot's screen will be @{b}moved to
front@{ub}.   If  it was @{b}iconified@{ub}, it will open again.  You can also @{b}load a base@{ub}
by @{b}dragging and dropping@{ub} its icon into the appicon.  See below.

    If  you  run  Polyglot  @{b}again@{ub}, when one was working, the second one will
exit  automatically.   Before  that,  it will tell the first one to move its
screen  to  front  (of  deiconify)  and  (if need) @{b}load a base@{ub} entered as an
argument to the first.

    If  you  try  to @{b}load a base@{ub} by appicon or restart the program, Polyglot
tries  to  identify  the file and - if it's valid - ask if you want to load.
If  you are in @{b}main menu@{ub} (or were iconified) the base is @{b}loaded@{ub} at once (you
may  save the previous one before).  If you are in other window, the program
tells you must @{b}return@{ub} to the main menu to load the base.  When you come back
to main menu, the programs load the base (asking you again).

@endnode

@node SaveB "Saving"
@next SaveB
@toc LoSav

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Saving a base@{fg text}@{ub}

    If  you  want  to  save  a  base to a disk, press @{b}@{fg fill}Save@{ub}@{fg text} in the main menu.
Also, if you @{b}change a base@{ub} with which you're working, and then want to quit,
load or create a @{b}new one@{ub}, Polyglot will ask if you want to @{b}save@{ub} it.
    A  @{b}requester@{ub}  will  appear, in which you may enter (or select) a name of
file  -  default  one  is  the  last loaded or saved.  It must have a '@{b}@{fg fill}.plg@{ub}@{fg text}'
@{b}extension@{ub}, else it will be added.

    If you set the @{b}Safe Saving@{ub} flag in @{" preferences " link Prefs}, Polyglot will check if
a  file  of  that name already exists.  If so, it will make a @{b}temporary copy@{ub}
called '@{b}@{fg fill}_pol_temp.plg@{ub}@{fg text}', and then save the new one.  Thanks to this you'll be
able to @{b}restore@{ub} previous version in case of error (see @{" errors " link ErSav}).
    After  saving  a base, there will be an @{b}icon@{ub} created if you set the @{b}@{fg fill}ICON@{ub}@{fg text}
parameter  (see  @{" running " link RunWb}).   The title of a base will be also saved in its
@{b}@{fg fill}comment@{ub}@{fg text}.

@endnode

@remark #############################################################


@node Prefs "Screen settings"
@prev LoSav
@next Edito
@{i}
    The  program screen is opened under system and it may be set in any way.
Read  @{" first  running " link FirRu}  to  get  know  about creating the prefs file - if it
doesn't exist, default mode (as Workbench screen) will be used.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Preferences window@{fg text}@{ub}

    Pubscr. name: @{"   " link PubSc} [_________________]
         Colours: [__|__|__|__|__|__| @{"[?]" link Color}
     Screen mode: [_________________] @{"[?]" link ScrMd}
     Screen font: [_________________] @{"[?]" link FontS}
     Beeping scr. @{"   " link Beepi} Safe saving: @{"   " link ErSav}
    [  Load  ]  [ Restore ]  [ Default  ]
    [  Save  ]  [   Use   ]  @{"   Cancel   " link MainM}

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Basic operations@{fg text}@{ub}

@{b}Load@{ub}  -  tries  to  load  a  preferences  file (set by the PREFS tooltype of
@{" icon " link RunWb}).

@{b}Restore@{ub} - restores the last used prefs (before calling prefs).

@{b}Default@{ub} - sets the default prefs (like Workbench).

@{b}Save@{ub} - saves the prefs to disk.

@{b}Use@{ub} - tries to open a window with new parameters.

@{b}Cancel@{ub} - exits window without changes.

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Preferences@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{" Public screen  " link PubSc}
    @{" Screen mode    " link ScrMd}
    @{" Colour palette " link Color}
    @{" Screen font    " link FontS}
    @{" Beeping screen " link Beepi}
    @{" Safe saving    " link ErSav}

@endnode


@node PubSc "Pubscreen"
@prev PubSc
@toc Prefs

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Public screen@{fg text}@{ub}

   Polyglot  always  opens  its  @{b}own  screen@{ub}.  It may be @{b}public@{ub} to let other
programs  open  their  windows  on  it.   You  have to enter its @{b}public name@{ub}
(default is @{b}@{fg fill}POLYGLOT@{ub}@{fg text}) and check the checkbox.  It's no possible to conflict,
because  there  may  be  only one Polyglot open, but remember that this name
must not be used by other screens.

    On a public screen you may e.g.:

 o  Open  a @{b}Shell window@{ub}.  In the Shell icon you may enter a @{b}@{fg fill}WINDOW@{ub}@{fg text} tooltype
which defines the window (more info in AmigaDOS docs), like this:
   @{b}@{fg fill}WINDOW=CON:x/y/width/height/title@{ub}@{fg text}
    You  may  add  other options (separated with / slashes).  One of them is
@{b}@{fg fill}SCREENname@{ub}@{fg text} (without spaces), name is a public screen name, e.g.:
   @{b}@{fg fill}WINDOW=CON:0/156/640/100/Shell/CLOSE/SCREENPOLYGLOT@{ub}@{fg text}

 o  Open  a  @{b}MultiView  document@{ub}  (like  this  doc you're reading!), using a
@{b}@{fg fill}PUBSCREEN=name@{ub}@{fg text} tooltype or Shell argument.

 o  There  are  many @{b}other programs@{ub} which lets you open their windows on any
@{b}public  screen@{ub}  with a parameter such as @{b}@{fg fill}PUBSCREEN@{ub}@{fg text}.  It's comfortable if you
use e.g.  dictionary-programs, text files etc.  There are also programs that
lets  you  use  any  screen  as  default screen (like ScreenSelect), so this
option is very useful.

    @{b}WARNING@{ub}.   Don't give a name which may be used by any other screens.  If
a  screen  which  has  @{b}the  same  name@{ub} exists, Polyglot will make its screen
@{b}private@{ub}.  You should use the default @{b}@{fg fill}POLYGLOT@{ub}@{fg text} name.

@endnode

@node Color "Colours..."
@toc Prefs

    The program screen has always @{b}eight colours@{ub}, independent of what mode it
uses.   It @{b}saves memory@{ub} and speed but looks very @{b}nice@{ub}.  Polyglot doesn't use
more colours at all (see @{" interface " link Inter}).
    The  @{b}colour  palette@{ub}  is set in such way that you don't have to set pens
for  different  elements  and  the  palette separately.  All @{b}elements@{ub} of the
interface has one @{b}corresponding colour@{ub} in the palette, but you can adjust it
to your needs.
    @{i}Note  that the program uses an AGA palette if it is possible (SetRGB32).
Else it uses old SetRGB4, but stores the colours always as 32bits.@{ui}

@{b}Colour no.0@{ub} - def. grey, screen background and all gadgets.
@{b}Colour no.1@{ub} - def. black, gadget texts and other texts (also in requesters).
    In OS2.x also the title bar of screen.
@{b}Colour no.2@{ub} - def. white, in OS3.0+ title bar of screen  and error  messages
    (in statuses). In 2.x - hmm... perhaps only the logo texts in main menu?
@{b}Colour no.3@{ub} - def. blue, active window frame,  pressed button background and
    info about a good answer in test.
@{b}Colour no.4@{ub} - def. very dark grey, shadow of gadgets and window frame.
@{b}Colour no.5@{ub} - def. very light grey, shines of gadgets and window frame.
@{b}Colour no.6@{ub} - def. beige, background of windows of Polyglot.
@{b}Colour no.7@{ub} - def. pink, info about wrong answer in test.

    The  @{b}default  palette@{ub}  is  based  on the MagicWB, it's a bit "soft".  If
somebody  prefers  something  more  "expressive"  -  well,  thanks  to using
separated  colours  of shine and shadow you can make very colourful effects.
If  somebody  prefers  less  colours  -  you  only  have  to make the window
background grey...

@endnode

@node ScrMd "Resolution"
@toc Prefs

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Screen mode@{fg text}@{ub}

    After pressing the @{b}@{fg fill}[?]@{ub}@{fg text} @{b}popup@{ub}, a screenmode @{b}requester@{ub} appears (reqtools).
It has a list of @{b}available modes@{ub} (depending on installed monitor drivers).
    You  may  also set the screen size - @{b}Overscan@{ub}.  There is a regular size,
text overscan (best - all screen visible), graphics (all monitor's area) and
maximum  size.  The text and gfx overscan may be set with the Overscan prefs
program.
    Setting  the  @{b}Autoscroll@{ub} flag  makes the screen scroll when it's not all
visible.

    If  there's  @{b}no prefs@{ub} file (or you choose @{b}Default@{ub}) the mode of @{b}Workbench@{ub}
will  be  used  (or  PAL  Hires  if  no  Wb  screen)  and Text Overscan with
Autoscroll.

    The program tries to open such screen as you chose.  But the screen mode
may  be  @{b}not available@{ub} (e.g.  needs AGA) or just there is @{b}not enough memory@{ub}.
The  screen  tries open in @{b}default mode@{ub} then.  If it's okay now it will only
warn you, else - it will resign.
@{i}
    A  screen  can  use  two  @{b}OS3.0+ features@{ub} - newlook (white menu bar) and
interleaved   bitmap  (more  smooth  graphics  operations  like  moving  the
windows).
@{ui}
@endnode

@node FontS "Screen font"
@toc Prefs

    @{b}@{fg highlight}The font@{fg text}@{ub}

    The  @{b}font@{ub} should be @{b}proportional@{ub} - it looks just much better.  Size of a
window  depends of the @{b}font size@{ub} (fully scaled).  Because it must fit on the
screen,  the  font  mustn't  be @{b}too big@{ub}.  In such case it's decreased.  On a
screen  with  256 points height maximum font size is eight, on 512 - sixteen
etc.
    The @{b}width@{ub} is free, but it shouldn't be too big too because the texts may
get off the gadgets.  For a standard 640 width you may use 8 and even 9 (its
mediocre size if proportional font).

    If  the  font @{b}can not be opened@{ub}, the program will try to use the @{b}default@{ub}
Workbench  font  (that  is  Screen  Text  in Font prefs).  It's decreased if
necessary. It it fails too, topaz is used.
@{i}
    If  a font of given size doesn't exist, it will be created by decreasing
an  existing one.  It looks awful (bitmap fonts) but it happens sometimes if
program  decrease  the  font  to fit on screen.  Just select something other
then.
@{ui}
@endnode

@node Beepi "Beeping while errors"
@next Beepi
@toc Prefs

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Beeping screen@{fg text}@{ub}

    If  this  flag is set, the program may generate a @{b}DisplayBeep@{ub} in case of
error  (only  @{b}status@{ub}-errors, not requesters).  It makes the screen @{b}flash@{ub} and
sometimes a @{b}beep-sound@{ub} (depends on the Sound prefs).
    I know that many people hate it so I let you @{b}turn it off@{ub}.  But sometimes
it's  useful,  when  somebody use the keyboard without looking on the screen
(like me :^).  It just may help you.

    By the way, the system generates such beep when you enter something into
the  string  gadget  and overload it.  It can't be turned off (unless with a
special program).

@endnode

@remark #############################################################


@node Edito "Test editor"
@prev Prefs
@next LeTst
@{i}
    See also editing different types of groups in @{" theory " link GrTyp} and @{" practice " link Pract}.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Editor window@{fg text}@{ub}

            @{"  Editing field depending on group type  " link GrTyp}

    Record: [###______________] [____]  Group: [___________]
    Status: [________________________]  @{"   Add   " link AddRe} @{"  Delete  " link DelRe}
    @{"  Change gr. " link GrpCh} @{"  Search  " link Searc} @{"  Sort  " link Sorti}  @{"   Edit  " link EdiRe} @{"   Exit   " link MainM}

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Basic operations@{fg text}@{ub}

    You can choose the current record with the @{b}record selection slider@{ub}.  You
can  use  @{b}mouse@{ub}  or  @{b}cursor@{ub} keys (@{b}@{fg fill}<-@{ub}@{fg text} and @{b}@{fg fill}->@{ub}@{fg text}, with @{b}@{fg fill}Shift@{ub}@{fg text} - jump 5 pos.).  The
record @{b}editing field@{ub} (above) depends on type of group you edit.
    Next  to  the  slider,  there  is an @{b}information@{ub} about current and total
record  number  and  also  the name of current group.  The @{b}status@{ub} is an info
about current operation.
    To  @{b}exit@{ub}  the  editor,  you  have to press the @{b}@{fg fill}Exit@{ub}@{fg text} button (or @{b}@{fg fill}ESC@{ub}@{fg text}), but
sometimes  (e.g.   during  editing  a  group)  it only @{b}breaks the operation@{ub}.
@{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} is a shortcut for the @{b}@{fg fill}Edit@{ub}@{fg text} key which @{b}starts editing@{ub} current record.
    You  may  also  @{" change  the  group " link GrpCh}  from  the editor (more changes are
available then).

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Record operations@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{" Adding a new record " link AddRe}
    @{" Changing the record " link EdiRe}
    @{" Deleting the record " link DelRe}

    @{" Search for a string " link Searc}
    @{" Sort records        " link Sorti}

@endnode

@node AddRe "A new record"
@prev AddRe
@toc Edito

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Adding a new record@{fg text}@{ub}

    You  have to press @{b}@{fg fill}Add@{ub}@{fg text} (or @{b}@{fg fill}a@{ub}@{fg text} key).  Remember that there may be up to 256
records  in  one group.  The edition of a record is very @{b}various@{ub} - depending
on its type, size and special flags.  More info in @{" group types " link GrTyp}.
    The  @{b}string gadgets@{ub} are cleared (except the same questions) when you add
new  record.   The  first  gadget  is  activated, the next are automatically
@{b}activated@{ub} when you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} (you can also use @{b}@{fg fill}TAB@{ub}@{fg text} key).
    When  you  @{b}finish@{ub} editing (by pressing @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} in last text field or using
the @{b}@{fg fill}Edit@{ub}@{fg text} key which means also 'Stop editing'), the program will check it and
@{b}correct  its  syntax@{ub}.   If the construction is valid the program will @{b}insert@{ub}
this  record  after the current one (you can change the slider position even
during  editing).   Else,  if  there  are  e.g.  no questions or no answers,
Polyglot  will  @{b}remove@{ub}  the  new  record.   The program may also @{b}change some
things@{ub}  if  needed (like deleting or moving some elements) and the text will
be @{" formatted " link Forma}.
    You  can  @{b}break@{ub} creating new record by pressing @{b}@{fg fill}ESC@{ub}@{fg text} (not during entering
text  into  string  - press @{b}@{fg fill}ESC@{ub}@{fg text} twice then) or the @{b}@{fg fill}Exit@{ub}@{fg text} key (which now means
'Exit from editing').

@endnode

@node EdiRe "Changing an existing record"
@toc Edito

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Editing a record@{fg text}@{ub}

    You may @{b}change@{ub} a created record in two ways.  If you want to change @{b}only
one@{ub}  or two @{b}text@{ub}s, just @{b}activate@{ub} the string gadget with @{b}mouse@{ub} and change its
contents.   The  program will check it, format and @{b}modify@{ub} the record if it's
correct.  In other case - it will restore previous contents.  You can change
the  @{b}checked answers@{ub} in choose test - simply change the check with mouse and
it will be changed in the record.
    @{b}Warning!@{ub}   If  you change a text manually, you have to press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} after
editing.   The program don't activate next strings in this mode, but you may
use  @{b}@{fg fill}TAB@{ub}@{fg text}  and  @{b}@{fg fill}Shift-TAB@{ub}@{fg text}  to move through the string.  Changes are @{b}confirmed@{ub}
only if you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}.

    The other way is @{b}changing all@{ub} the record.  When you press @{b}@{fg fill}Edit@{ub}@{fg text} (or @{b}@{fg fill}e@{ub}@{fg text} key
or  just  the  @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} key!), the first field (string gadget) is activated and
after  pressing @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} the next is @{b}activated@{ub} too.  As during adding a record,
changes  are @{b}confirmed@{ub} when you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} in last field or the @{b}@{fg fill}Edit@{ub}@{fg text} gadget
again.   @{b}@{fg fill}Exit@{ub}@{fg text}  (@{b}@{fg fill}ESC@{ub}@{fg text})  cancels  the  changes.   Of  course the record will be
@{b}checked@{ub} and parsed again.

@endnode

@node DelRe "Deleting"
@toc Edito

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Deleting a record@{fg text}@{ub}

    When you press @{b}@{fg fill}Delete@{ub}@{fg text} (or @{b}@{fg fill}d@{ub}@{fg text} key), the current record is @{b}deleted@{ub}.  If you
choose this button during editing (or adding), the changes are cancelled.
    @{b}Warning@{ub}:  the delete operation is not confirmed!

@endnode

@node Searc "Searching for a text in records"
@toc Edito

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Searching a text@{fg text}@{ub}

    You  can  search  for  any  word, string etc.  if you have more than one
record.   When you press @{b}@{fg fill}Search@{ub}@{fg text}, a @{b}requester@{ub} will appear.  You have to enter
the  @{b}string@{ub} (one or more letters or words or anything), and select searching
@{b}forwards@{ub} or @{b}backwards@{ub} (from the current record).  The last entered string is
remembered.

    The  programs  searches  the records in turn, every question and answer.
The  entered search string is stored @{b}as it is@{ub} (no formatting), it's not case
sensitive (unless you've set the Upper<>lower flag).  It may be found in any
place of a string.

    If  the  string is found, the editor @{b}skips to the record@{ub} in which it is.
Else, it will only show a status info.

    If  you  want  to find the @{b}same text@{ub} in several records, call the @{b}@{fg fill}Search@{ub}@{fg text}
option  and  only  press @{b}@{fg fill}Forward@{ub}@{fg text} or @{b}@{fg fill}Backward@{ub}@{fg text} without changing the text.  You
can  use  @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}  for  forward  and  @{b}@{fg fill}rAmiga + b@{ub}@{fg text} for backward searching in the
requester.
    If  the  record  in  which  the  string was @{b}found last time@{ub} is currently
displayed,  it's  @{b}skipped@{ub} (unless you change something).  Thanks to that you
won't find the same text in the same place.

@endnode


@node Sorti "Alphabetical sorting"
@next Sorti
@toc Edito

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Sorting the records@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{b}Alphabetical  sorting@{ub}  the  records in a group makes the work with large
records  easier.   It  doesn't  change  the  contents  but only the @{b}order@{ub} of
records.   Remember  that  during  learning/test the questions are in random
order anyway.
    Before sorting the program checks if there are minimum 2 records to sort
:),  then  it  will ask you to @{b}confirm@{ub}.  If it's the simple phrases test, it
will  also  ask  if you want the group sorted by @{b}questions@{ub} (1st language) or
@{b}answers@{ub}  (2nd  language).   In other types the group is sorted always by the
main (upper) question.
    The  operation  is  @{b}very  fast@{ub}  (iterative quicksort used :).  When it's
done, the first record in new order will be displayed in the editor.
    Warning:   The  sort-routine  sorts  properly  all  national letters (at
present  Polish  letters  are  included,  but  most important other national
characters are on the proper place).  It checks also the case of letters and
all punctuation marks.

@endnode

@remark #############################################################


@node LeTst "Learning and Test"
@prev Edito
@{i}
    See also @{" test forms " link GrTyp} and @{" efficient learning " link Learn}.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Test window@{fg text}@{ub}

            @{"  Test field depending on group type  " link GrTyp}

       Answers: [########________________________] [_____] [____]
    Good/Wrong: [#############___________________] [_____] [____]
    Status: [_____________] Time: [_____]  [  Okay  ]  @{"  Cancel  " link MainM}

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Learning and test@{fg text}@{ub}

    The  questions  are always asked in @{b}random order@{ub}.  In the @{b}learning@{ub} mode,
the  wrong answered questions is @{b}repeated@{ub} as long as your answer is correct.
You  can  repeat  those  questions which are most difficult to you and learn
them.   The  learning  is  done when you answer correctly on every question.
That's why you shouldn't make the groups too big.
    In the @{b}test@{ub} mode each question is asked @{b}only once@{ub}.  You can easily check
your progress.

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Fields and options@{fg text}@{ub}

    In  the  upper part there are @{b}questions@{ub}, @{b}answers@{ub} which you have to enter
and  @{b}correct  answers@{ub}  displayed  in  case  of  error.  Its form and service
depends on the @{" group type " link GrTyp}.
    In  the  lower part, there is a full @{b}information@{ub} displayed - a graphical
indicator,   number  and  percent  of  questions  you've  @{b}answered@{ub}  and  the
proportion of @{b}good and wrong@{ub} answers (blue/red colour).

    When  a  question  is given, the program waits until you fill all string
gadgets  with  answers or check the choose answers.  When you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} in
the last gadget or press @{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text}, your answer is @{b}checked@{ub}.

    If  you answer well, the program will display a status.  If you make any
@{b}error@{ub},  there  will  be  also  a  list  of @{b}good answers@{ub} displayed to let you
remember  them.   The  indicators are updated.  When you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} or @{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text}
again, the program asks you another question.

    There  is  @{b}no time limit@{ub} in the test, but you can check yourself, so the
@{b}@{fg fill}Time@{ub}@{fg text}  is displayed.  It's in a hours:minutes format.  You can break the test
or learning in any moment by pressing @{b}@{fg fill}Cancel@{ub}@{fg text} (@{b}@{fg fill}ESC@{ub}@{fg text}) and confirming it.

    When  the  test  is  @{b}all  done@{ub},  the program shows a @{b}requester@{ub} with your
results.   It  doesn't  give you a note, only a percentage score.  The other
information and test time is still displayed in the test main window.

@endnode

@remark ###############################################################


@node GrTyp "Types of group, configuration, service"
@next Pract
@{i}
    You  can  find  the information about three types of groups, setting and
using  them  and  edition/test  of  the  types.   See  also  next node about
practical use of these groups.
@{ui}
    @{b}@{fg highlight}Group types@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{" Simple phrases, words etc.    " link GrSim}
    @{" Edit test - groups of phrases " link GrEdi}
    @{" Choose test (or multitest)    " link GeCho}

    @{" Formatting strings            " link Forma}

@endnode

@node GrSim "Simple group type"
@prev GrSim
@toc GrTyp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Simple phrases@{fg text}@{ub}

    This is the only test in which the construction of answers and questions
is  @{b}identical@{ub},  and  you  may  do it either from 1st language to 2nd or @{b}vice
versa@{ub}.

    This  type of test is good for @{b}simple phrases@{ub} and @{b}words@{ub}, but not for the
complex sentences.  Read the practice chapter about style of building tests.

    @{b}Configuration@{ub}

    Both  answers  and questions are just @{b}phrases@{ub} (words, phrases, sentences
etc.),  which may have from 1 to 5 @{b}synonyms@{ub}.  During the learning/test there
is only @{b}one@{ub} question and you may enter only @{b}one@{ub} answer.  Because the answers
are  often  ambiguous (e.g.  search - seek - look for, etc.  or like don't -
do  not), you may give several @{b}equivalent@{ub} versions.  There will be only one,
chosen  randomly,  version  in  the  question,  you may give any form as the
answer.  All good answers are displayed if you answer wrong.
    You  may  select  the  number  of  synonyms using the @{b}@{fg fill}Rows@{ub}@{fg text} slider in the
@{" group settings " link GrpOp} window.

    You  may  also  decide  if  the  upper  and lower @{b}case@{ub} is different (the
@{b}@{fg fill}Upper<>Lower@{ub}@{fg text}  flag)  like e.g.  German @{b}@{fg fill}sie@{ub}@{fg text} and @{b}@{fg fill}Sie@{ub}@{fg text}, or it's the same (a @{b}@{fg fill}word@{ub}@{fg text}
equals a @{b}@{fg fill}WORD@{ub}@{fg text}).

    In   more   complex  constructions  the  simple  synonyms  will  be  not
sufficient.   Often  one English word is corresponding to several completely
different foreign meanings and vice versa.  If you turn the @{b}@{fg fill}[] Comments@{ub}@{fg text} flag
on,  you  can  add  @{b}special comments@{ub} in @{b}@{fg fill}[]@{ub}@{fg text} brackets after the main part of a
phrase,  like  a specific description.  It's displayed in @{b}questions@{ub} and good
answers  list,  but  you @{b}needn't@{ub} (even mustn't) enter it in the answer.  See
@{" practice " link Pract} for examples.
    When this option is off, you can't use the @{b}@{fg fill}[ ]@{ub}@{fg text} signs in strings (they'll
be removed).  The brackets are always @{" formatted " link Forma}.

    @{b}Editing@{ub}

    During  @{" edition " link EdiRe}  (or  @{" adding " link AddRe})  a  record,  you  have  to  enter the
@{b}corresponding  phrases@{ub}  -  first in first language, then in second one.  You
have  to  enter @{b}at least one@{ub} synonym in each language.  After pressing @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}
(or  @{b}@{fg fill}TAB@{ub}@{fg text})  the  next  field will be @{b}activated@{ub}.  You may fill @{b}not every@{ub} field
(just  press  an  'empty'  @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}).   All  phrases will be @{b}formatted@{ub} to avoid
troubles with spaces and brackets.
    You  can also @{b}modify one phrase@{ub} by clicking on it, changing and pressing
@{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text}.  One phrase may be up to 69 chars long.
@{b}@{fg fill}
        [phrase 1 in 1st language] \_ synonyms
        [phrase 2 in 1st language] //
        ...
        [phrase 1 in 2nd language]
        [phrase 2 in 2nd language]
        ...
@{ub}@{fg text}
    @{b}Test and learning@{ub}

    The  @{" test/learning " link LeTst}  is  very  simple.   First  you  should  select the
@{b}question language@{ub}.  The random question is displayed in @{b}upper line@{ub}, you have
to  @{b}enter  answers@{ub}  into  the string gadget below.  If a given answer (after
formatting) doesn't match to any correct synonym answer, all of them will be
displayed  below.   A  little  @{b}tick@{ub}  (V or X) gadget shows if the answer was
correct or not.
@{b}@{fg fill}
        [question     ]
        (answer       )  <- you write here
        [X] [ answ. 1 ]
            [ answ. 2 ]
            ...
@{ub}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node GrEdi "Edit test"
@toc GrTyp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Edit test - group of phrases@{fg text}@{ub}

    This  is  a  '@{b}one-way@{ub}'  test,  that  means the questions are only in one
language.

    This  test  may  be  used  in  many  ways,  from a @{b}declination@{ub} of words,
learning whole @{b}groups@{ub} of words (or phrases), to @{b}filling sentences@{ub} with words
(grammatical tests) etc.  See also @{" practical " link Pract} description.

    @{b}Configuration@{ub}

    There is always @{b}one main question@{ub}, different for each question, there is
a  number of @{b}sub-questions@{ub}, which may be @{b}same@{ub} (like declination names) - the
@{b}@{fg fill}Same  questions@{ub}@{fg text} in @{" group " link GrpOp} window, or @{b}different@{ub} for every record.  There may
be @{b}from 1 to 5@{ub} sub-questions (the @{b}@{fg fill}Rows@{ub}@{fg text} slider).

    You  may  turn  on  the @{b}distinction@{ub} of upper and lower @{b}case@{ub} (like in the
previous @{" type " link GrSim}).
    The  last flag (@{b}@{fg fill}Empty = *@{ub}@{fg text}) is a help for the learning person.  It's only
available  in @{b}same questions@{ub} test.  Because of that you may create questions
@{b}without  answers@{ub} in this mode (e.g.  mixing regular and irregular verbs) and
writing  anything here would be an error, you may let the program @{b}mark@{ub} those
empty  answers  with  an  asterisk  (@{b}@{fg fill}*@{ub}@{fg text}).   Sometimes  you just needn't enter
everything  if  it's obvious.  The @{b}@{fg fill}*@{ub}@{fg text} let you know what you have to enter and
what not.
    If  the  sub-questions are not the same, there @{b}must@{ub} be an answer to each
question (but there may be less questions than the rows in a record).

    @{b}Editing@{ub}

    During the adding and editing a record, all text fields are linked (that
means  @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} moves you to the next field) and confirmed by pressing @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} in
last field.  You may also change @{b}single@{ub} fields.  See @{" editing " link Edito}.

    The  @{b}main question@{ub} on the top @{b}must@{ub} be entered.  It's different for every
record.
    If  the  @{b}sub-questions@{ub} are @{b}same@{ub} (see above), you must enter @{b}all of them@{ub}.
If  you  change  them  in  one  record,  they change in each other too.  The
answers may be entered by @{b}any@{ub} of the questions (at least one), there are two
forms available (@{b}synonyms@{ub}).
    If  the  sub-questions  are  @{b}different@{ub}, you may enter @{b}any number@{ub} of them
(different  for  each  record  too), but each must have at least one @{b}answer@{ub}.
Every text in both cases is checked and @{" formatted " link Forma}.
@{b}@{fg fill}
        [main question     ]
        [subq. 1] [answer 1]
                  [answer 2]
        [subq. 2] [answer 1]
                  [answer 2]
        ....
@{ub}@{fg text}
    @{b}Test and learning@{ub}

    In  a @{" test " link LeTst} there is the @{b}main@{ub} question and @{b}all sub-questions@{ub} displayed.
In not-same questions, you must enter as many answers as the questions.

    If  the sub-questions are @{b}same@{ub}, the 'empty' answers are also checked (if
there's  e.g.   no  form  for a word - if you enter something, it will be an
error).   The  @{b}@{fg fill}Empty = *@{ub}@{fg text}  option (above) makes the empty answers @{b}marked@{ub} with
an  asterisk  -  you know then you needn't enter anything here.  The answers
beginning  with  a  @{b}@{fg fill}*@{ub}@{fg text} mark are treated as @{b}empty@{ub} ones (only in same questions
test).

    The  answer  is  recognized  as  @{b}good@{ub} only if @{b}all@{ub} of the sub-answers are
good.  Else, the errors and good answers are shown.
@{b}@{fg fill}
        [main question       ]
        subdue ] (answer    ) -
         [X] [answ.1] [answ.2]   <- write your answers here
        [subq.2 ] (answer    ) -
         [X] [answ.1] [answ.2]
        ....      ....
@{ub}@{fg text}
@endnode


@node GrCho "Option choose test"
@toc GrTyp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Choose test@{fg text}@{ub}

    All  text  is  mostly in first language (but it's not necessary) in this
test.   It's  similar  to  the previous one, but you don't have to enter the
answer but just @{b}choose@{ub} (check) that option you recognize as @{b}good@{ub}.

    This  test  is  used  mostly to complete sentences or choose the correct
version  (e.g.   after  a  translation or conversion), see @{" practice " link Pract}.  It's
much  more  @{b}grammatical@{ub},  because  there's  no  such  ambiguity  in  complex
sentences as while editing answers.

    @{b}Configuration@{ub}

    There  is  one  @{b}main question@{ub}, and some @{b}options@{ub} to choose.  There may be
from  2  to 5 options (@{b}@{fg fill}Rows@{ub}@{fg text} in the @{" group " link GrpOp} window) in one or two @{b}independent
columns@{ub}  (@{b}@{fg fill}Cols@{ub}@{fg text}).   Normally,  only @{b}one@{ub} option (answer) may be @{b}checked@{ub} in one
column.   You  may also turn on the @{b}@{fg fill}Multitest@{ub}@{fg text} mode in which there may be @{b}any
number@{ub} of good (checked) answers.

    @{b}Editing@{ub}

    When  you @{" edit " link EdiRe} or @{" add " link AddRe} a record, you have to write the @{b}main question@{ub}
and  then  the  options  (answers)  - @{b}at least two@{ub} in each column.  All text
fields  are  @{b}linked@{ub} (like in two other types), to confirm changes just press
@{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} in last field.  You can change also only a @{b}single@{ub} field.

    When you create a new record, the first answer is checked by default (or
all  are negative in multitest mode).  You can @{b}change@{ub} it in any moment (best
is just after entering the text), using @{b}mouse only@{ub}.  Use the @{b}checkbuttons@{ub} to
do it.
@{b}@{fg fill}
        [question                    ]
        [V] [option 1]  [V] [option 1]
        [V] [option 2]  [V] [option 2]
        ....            ....
@{ub}@{fg text}
    @{b}Test and learning@{ub}

    In  @{" test " link LeTst}  the  @{b}question@{ub}  and @{b}all options@{ub} to choose are displayed.  The
first  option is selected by default (or none in multitest).  You can @{b}select
the  answer@{ub}  you  recognize  as  a  good one (ore ones in multitest) in each
column  using  the  mouse  - @{b}checkbuttons@{ub}.  The answer will be @{b}checked@{ub} (in a
very  simple way :) when you press @{b}@{fg fill}ENTER@{ub}@{fg text} (or @{b}@{fg fill}Okay@{ub}@{fg text}) and if wrong - shown with
the @{b}tick@{ub}-gadgets (X or V and blue or red background).
@{b}@{fg fill}
    [question             ]
    [ ] [V] [option 1] ....
    [ ] [ ] [option 2]
     |   |
     |   chosen option
     note
@{ub}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Forma "Formatting the text"
@next Forma
@toc GrTyp

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Formatting the text@{fg text}@{ub}

    The  program  @{b}formats@{ub}  every  entered  text  to  avoid  such  errors  as
unnecessary space etc.  It @{b}removes@{ub} every @{b}space@{ub} at the beginning and end of a
string and every space over one inside the text.
    The  @{b}@{fg fill}[  ]@{ub}@{fg text}  brackets  are @{b}removed@{ub} (if not needed) or - in the @{b}@{fg fill}[] Comments@{ub}@{fg text}
mode - @{b}modified@{ub} in that way, the bracket is always at the @{b}end@{ub} of string (the
following text will be removed) and has exactly one @{b}@{fg fill}[@{ub}@{fg text} and one @{b}@{fg fill}]@{ub}@{fg text}.
    This formatting is done during @{" editing " link Edito} and @{" learning/test " link LeTst}.

    See  also  more notes about the style and organization of records in the
@{" style " link Style}.

@endnode

@remark ##############################################################


@node Pract "Using Polyglot in practice"
@prev GrTyp
@next Error

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Practice@{fg text}@{ub}
@{i}
    The example data base called '@{b}@{fg fill}Example.plg@{ub}@{fg text}' in the '@{b}@{fg fill}Bases@{ub}@{fg text}' directory is a
good  example  which will help you getting known the program.  You need some
practice  to  create  new  bases (that is what's the program for).  See also
configuration and service of @{" groups " link GrTyp}.
    I'm  sure  that  you  can  use the program now and know the basic things
about it when you read this.

    Note  that  the  examples  are English-German (I guess not everyone know
Polish :^), hope you will 'verstehen'.
@{ui}

    @{" Efficient learning with Polyglot        " link Learn}

    @{" Simple phrases and words                " link PrPhr}
    @{" Groups & decl. of words, simple grammar " link PrEdi}
    @{" Choose tests (mostly grammatical)       " link PrCho}

    @{" Style of own data bases                 " link Style}

@endnode

@node Learn "How to learn?"
@prev Learn
@toc Pract

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Learning with Polyglot@{fg text}@{ub}

    As I said at the beginning, the main function of this program is @{b}to help
you  learning@{ub}  foreign  languages @{b}yourself@{ub}, mainly @{b}words, phrases and simple
grammatical tests@{ub}.
    It's designed for people who can @{b}learn well themselves@{ub} (or directed by a
teacher)  and  know the language a bit.  It's not important what language it
is,  but  how  do  you  learn it.  I'm not a linguist, but I wrote it mainly
because I wanted a program to do that.

    Beside  the  @{b}grammar@{ub},  we  learn  many  @{b}words and phrases@{ub} from texts and
exercises.   We  write  them  on  a  paper (or exercise-book) to @{b}learn@{ub} it by
repeating them from time to time (the more frequently - the better).  We can
also @{b}check@{ub} our knowledge or progress before a test or exam.

    And  here  comes the Polyglot with invaluable help.  Using this program,
we  may  in  a  comfortable  way (if we know something about the keyboard :)
@{b}create  bases@{ub}  from @{b}new material@{ub}, repeat the @{b}tests@{ub} and @{b}learn systematically@{ub},
and  @{b}check@{ub} our knowledge.  Because there may be several @{b}groups@{ub}, we can learn
@{b}partly@{ub} and add new things to the groups.

@endnode


@node PrPhr "Application of phrases test"
@toc Pract

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Simple phrases@{fg text}@{ub}

    This  test  is  best  for  learning  @{b}simple@{ub}  (and  single) @{b}words@{ub} (nouns,
adjectives,  regular  verbs etc.) and @{b}simple phrases@{ub}, expressions etc.  Some
people  use  it  to  learn whole sentences but it's senseless, because every
sentence  may  be  translated in hundreds ways (more or less correct).  This
program  checks  everything  @{b}by  a letter@{ub} (even dots and commas), not by the
meaning.   The  only  exception  are  the  spaces  (text  is  formatted) and
upper/lower case (but these may be distinguished too).

    The  simplest  examples  like  @{b}@{fg fill}table-der Tisch@{ub}@{fg text}, @{b}@{fg fill}chair-das Stuhl@{ub}@{fg text}, may get
complicated  sometimes.   For  example the @{b}synonyms@{ub} needs several rows, e.g.
@{b}@{fg fill}search, seek, look for - suchen, benötigen, fahnden@{ub}@{fg text}.

    To  avoid  such synonyms as @{b}@{fg fill}don't - do not@{ub}@{fg text} or @{b}@{fg fill}apple - apples@{ub}@{fg text}, you should
specify  what  @{b}kind  of  words@{ub}  should  the  user write (abbreviated - full,
singular - plural etc.) and put it into the @{b}description@{ub}.  You shouldn't also
mix several parts of speech.

    There are often very complicated @{b}combinations of words@{ub}.  For example, @{b}@{fg fill}go@{ub}@{fg text}
means  (in  German,  of  course)  @{b}@{fg fill}gehen,  fahren@{ub}@{fg text}.  @{b}@{fg fill}Gehen@{ub}@{fg text} means @{b}@{fg fill}go@{ub}@{fg text} and @{b}@{fg fill}leave@{ub}@{fg text}.
@{b}@{fg fill}Fahren@{ub}@{fg text}  means  @{b}@{fg fill}go@{ub}@{fg text}  and  @{b}@{fg fill}transport@{ub}@{fg text}.  @{b}@{fg fill}Leave@{ub}@{fg text} means @{b}@{fg fill}verlassen@{ub}@{fg text}.  And so on.  This
example  is not the best (the Polish version is better) but sometimes it may
happen to you.

    The   solution  is  quite  simple.   I  didn't  enter  more  complicated
structures  into  this  program (it's for linguist not the learners :) but I
entered  a  simple  system  of  @{b}comments@{ub} in @{b}@{fg fill}[]@{ub}@{fg text} brackets which are added to a
phrase.   They're  displayed  in  questions,  but  not in the answers.  Why?
Because the test is 'two-directional'.
    Here's an example:
@{b}@{fg fill}        gehen - go [by walk], leave [go]
       fahren - go [by car], transport [go]
    verlassen - leave  @{ub}@{fg text}etc.

    You may do it of course in any other way, but I think it's the simplest.
You may see that @{b}@{fg fill}leave@{ub}@{fg text} is @{b}@{fg fill}verlassen@{ub}@{fg text}, but @{b}@{fg fill}leave [go]@{ub}@{fg text} is @{b}@{fg fill}gehen@{ub}@{fg text}.  I recall that
this  test  may  be asked in '@{b}other way@{ub}' (e.g.  German-English) and you must
still know what's going on.
@{i}
    See  the  examples  of  '@{b}@{fg fill}Simp_normal@{ub}@{fg text}' and '@{b}@{fg fill}Simp_comments@{ub}@{fg text}' in the example
base.   See  also  configuration and service of @{" simple phrases " link GtSim}, @{" test " link LeTst} and
@{" editing " link Edito}.
@{ui}
@endnode

@node PrEdi "Groups of phrases in practice"
@toc Pract

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Edit test - groups of phrases@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{b}Declination@{ub}

    It's  the  simplest application of edit test.  Set rows to the number of
@{b}forms@{ub}  and  set the @{b}@{fg fill}Same quests@{ub}@{fg text} flag to true (because the names of forms are
same).

    Sometimes  it's comfortable to use the @{b}@{fg fill}Empty = *@{ub}@{fg text} flag too.  First reason
is  that you may mix regular and irregular verbs - the user needn't to enter
the regular forms then.  If you enter something it will be an error (but you
may make the test harder too).
    Second  reason  is  when  some forms exists, but you needn't enter those
which  are  obvious.   If you want to know (during the test) which forms you
don't have to enter, just leave them empty and set the asterisks.
    An  example - '@{b}@{fg fill}Ed_declination@{ub}@{fg text}' group (some regular and irregular English
verbs).

    @{b}Groups of words@{ub}

    We  have  @{b}different sub-questions@{ub} here.  It lets us learn some groups of
words  or  phrases with the same word.  An example is phrasal verbs (and the
German ones...), like this:
@{b}@{fg fill}        put
        ~           hineinlegen, stecken
        put on      anziehen, anlegen
        put down    beiseitelegen ...@{ub}@{fg text}
    As  you  see  two  @{b}synonyms@{ub}  are used here (you have to enter one in the
test).
    You  can  learn different phrases with one word (you can use a @{b}@{fg fill}~@{ub}@{fg text} sign as
in dictionaries):
@{b}@{fg fill}        time
        ~                    die Zeit
        from ~ to ~          von Zeit zu Zeit
        in the course of ~   mit im Laufe der Zeit, mit der Zeit ...@{ub}@{fg text}
    You can also learn different meaning of a word (don't use @{b}@{fg fill}[]@{ub}@{fg text} but @{b}@{fg fill}()@{ub}@{fg text}! )
@{b}@{fg fill}        man
        (male)      der Mann
        (human)     der Mensch ...@{ub}@{fg text}

    Examples of such construction are in '@{b}@{fg fill}Ed_groups@{ub}@{fg text}' group.

    @{b}Grammar@{ub}

    As  I  wrote,  translating  the  whole  sentences has no sense (too many
combinations),  but  you  can  learn  the  @{b}application@{ub}  of  some  @{b}phrases in
sentences@{ub}.   It's  difficult  to create during learning, but you may rewrite
some exercises if you found it useful.  Several examples are included in the
'@{b}@{fg fill}Ed_grammar@{ub}@{fg text}' group.
    The  most  popular  test  is  @{b}completing  sentences@{ub}  with  translated or
converted words, e.g.:  (only English will be here :)
@{b}@{fg fill}        What (you, do) here when (he, come)?
        1.  were you doing
        2.  he came@{ub}@{fg text}
    Notice  that  you  may  use  the  @{b}same questions@{ub} here.  More complicated
grammatical tests should be in a @{b}choose test@{ub} (as I mentioned several times).
@{i}
    See  also  - configuration and service of @{" edit test " link GrEdi}, and @{" edit " link Edito}/@{" test " link LeTst}
with a group.
@{ui}
@endnode

@node PrCho "Choose test - practice"
@toc Pract

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Choose test@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{b}Grammar@{ub}

    It's  practically the @{b}only application@{ub} of this test.  It won't be useful
for  learning  words.   But  you  may  rewrite some exercises from a book to
repeat  grammar  from  time  to  time.  For completing sentences it's better
(usually)  to  use  the edit test (above), but if you have to use whole more
complicated constructions - a @{b}choose test@{ub} is better.
    A simple example is @{b}converting a sentence@{ub} from active to passive voice:
@{b}@{fg fill}      John is reading his a book in the room.
        The book reads John in the room.
        The book is reading by John in the room.
        The book is being read by John
        The room ....@{ub}@{fg text}
    Hmm,  yes...   You  may  also  use the @{b}@{fg fill}Multitest@{ub}@{fg text} to choose more than one
answers:
@{b}@{fg fill}      I have seen him.
        yesterday
        just
        not already
        not yet ....@{ub}@{fg text}

@{i}
    Such  types  of  test  are  included  in  '@{b}@{fg fill}Test_choose@{ub}@{fg text}' and '@{b}@{fg fill}Test_multi@{ub}@{fg text}'
groups.   See also - configuration and service of @{" choose tests " link GrCho}, @{" edit " link Edito} and
@{" learn/test " link LeTst}.
@{ui}
@endnode

@node Style "The Style"
@next Style
@toc Pract

    @{b}@{fg highlight}A style of creating tests@{fg text}@{ub}

    It  wouldn't  be necessary, but it @{b}helps@{ub}...  Especially if you look at a
base after a year...

    Of  course  I assume you know what do you want, and you have created and
@{" configurated " link GrTyp} a group to work.

    First you have to decide what @{b}kind of words@{ub} will you use - like @{b}@{fg fill}don't@{ub}@{fg text} or
@{b}@{fg fill}do  not@{ub}@{fg text}.   The  program won't do it itself.  You needn't write both synonyms
all the time if you decide.  That's why you should @{b}decide@{ub} (and describe it).

    The  similar  problem  is  with the @{b}punctuation marks@{ub}.  The program will
@{" format " link Forma}  spaces  and  @{b}@{fg fill}[]@{ub}@{fg text}  brackets, but not the @{b}@{fg fill}.,?!@{ub}@{fg text}  etc.  Other important
things  are  @{b}ordering  words@{ub}  in  a  record  (by  meaning, form etc.), using
@{b}comments@{ub},  @{b}@{fg fill}~@{ub}@{fg text}  marks  in  groups  of  words  etc.   It  helps you working and
learning.

    Also,  it's  important that you @{b}shouldn't@{ub} create too @{b}big groups@{ub}, because
you  must  always  learn all records in a group @{b}at all@{ub}.  You should use such
size as you like.  You can also learn and add new words at the @{b}same time@{ub}.
    It's  no  need  to use too @{b}complicated@{ub} records.  It's better to use more
records  with  less  words in each one.  Remember that one mistake means the
whole answer is incorrect.

    Beside  learning @{b}words and phrases@{ub} you may also rewrite some @{b}grammatical
tests@{ub}  from  any  exercise  book.   It's  more  comfortable than writing and
erasing  in  the  book  :)  You  needn't  learn  it by heart, but you should
recall some grammatical rules too (not the examples).

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Using descriptions@{fg text}@{ub}

    @{b}Describing@{ub}  your  bases  and  groups (see  @{" description " link Descr}) is a very good
habit.  It may include @{b}information@{ub} about the @{b}material@{ub} (and its source), @{b}date@{ub}
of  last  update (and learning :), and a full description of @{b}test form@{ub} used.
There  should  be  some info about @{b}what to enter@{ub} as the answers (and in what
form),  what  @{b}forms@{ub}  of words and @{b}syntax@{ub} should be used etc.  Thanks to this
you  may  quickly  @{b}find@{ub} this information and @{b}recall@{ub} the form and contents of
your tests (you will learn very long :).
@{i}
    More practical info may be found in my example base (called @{b}@{fg fill}Examples.plg@{ub}@{fg text}
- English-German, also a English-Polish version @{b}@{fg fill}Przyklady.plg@{ub}@{fg text} is included.
@{ui}
@endnode

@remark ###################################################################


@node Error "Errors and protections"
@prev Pract
@next Histo

    This  program  has  a simple @{b}error-protection system@{ub}, mostly @{b}disk errors@{ub}
and  low  @{b}memory@{ub}  situations.  It's rather unaffected by 'crazy ideas', it's
been @{b}tested deeply@{ub}.  But you can't be absolutely sure (see @{" disclaimer " link AfdCo 59}).

    @{" Memory management " link Memor}

    @{" Load errors       " link ErLoa}
    @{" Save errors       " link ErSav}

@endnode

@node Memor "If you have less..."
@prev Memor
@toc Error

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Memory management@{fg text}@{ub}

    People  with  4  and  more MB of memory don't have to read this.  If you
have  @{b}2MB@{ub}  you  may  use  this  program  @{b}freely@{ub} and work with big bases with
Workbench  open,  but  if  you  use  many other programs, you can run out of
memory.  The poor with @{b}1MB@{ub} should run it @{b}directly@{ub} (without Workbench) but it
should be possible to work.  See @{" running " link InsRu}.

    The program is rather @{b}economical@{ub} with memory.  Of course, much memory is
taken by the @{b}screen and windows@{ub}, so if it's impossible to open them you must
free  some memory (e.g.  remove unused programs, window etc.) and try again.
See also @{" screen and windows " link ScrWi}.

    Memory  for  the @{b}base@{ub} is allocated @{b}dynamically@{ub}, so it uses as much as it
@{b}needs@{ub}  in a moment.  But remember the operating system needs at least @{b}200 KB@{ub}
of @{b}free memory@{ub} to work properly.
    Polyglot displays the @{b}amount of free memory@{ub} (Chip and Fast) on the title
bar  of  its  screen.  If it will be less than @{b}250 KB@{ub}, it will tell you that
you  should  @{b}remove@{ub} unused things @{b}from memory@{ub}.  If it's less than 200 KB, it
will @{b}refuse@{ub} to work until you free the memory!
    Normally  the amount of memory doesn't change so quick, but it may do if
you work with several big programs.  So it checks memory even when @{b}loading@{ub} a
base (there must be min.  200 KB free).  If it runs of memory - it will load
only a @{b}part@{ub} of base.

    The  program  doesn't  allocate memory in pieces bigger than 1KB, but it
does  it  by  8KB  blocks  (pools).  It's @{b}almost impossible@{ub} that it couldn't
allocate  such  block,  but  if  it  would  happen  it will stop immediately
(Wait(0)...).  As I said the windows and requesters are more 'hungry'.

@endnode

@node ErLoa "Loading a base"
@toc Error

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Errors on loading@{fg text}@{ub}

    If you try to @{" load " link LoadB} a @{b}base file@{ub}, by the @{b}@{fg fill}Load@{ub}@{fg text} gadget or an @{" appicon " link Appic}, or
by the @{" BASE " link RunWb} argument, the file will be @{b}checked@{ub} before loading.  First, the
programs  tries  to  @{b}open a directory@{ub} (if the path doesn't contain a device,
assign etc.  with a :, it will be loaded relatively to the main directory of
Polyglot) or display an @{b}error@{ub} (only from main menu).

    The  @{b}name@{ub}  of every base must have a '@{b}@{fg fill}.plg@{ub}@{fg text}' @{b}extension@{ub}, which is added if
it doesn't exist.  The program checks if the file exists, and loads a bit to
check if it's a @{b}Polyglot base@{ub}.  Else - it will warn you.
    The @{b}length@{ub} of a file is also checked - if it's @{b}incomplete@{ub} (e.g.  because
of  saving  error  or  file corrupt) you will be warned (but it may be still
loaded partly).

    The program will start to read the base only if it's @{b}identified@{ub}.  If you
used  the  @{b}appicon@{ub},  you  have  to  go  to  @{b}main  menu@{ub} and confirm it again.
Polyglot  may  also ask if you want to save a previously @{b}changed base@{ub} (which
will be deleted before loading).

    The  program  loads  a  base  in  @{b}small  steps@{ub}.   It's  longer, but more
efficient (less memory used).  It also must be transformed a bit to make the
work faster (in memory).

    If the loading is @{b}interrupted@{ub} because of a @{b}disk error@{ub}, @{b}lack of memory@{ub} or
@{b}incomplete@{ub}  file,  the loaded part will be @{b}stored@{ub} in memory and you may work
with  it  without complications.  It lets you recover damaged files (but the
beginning must exist).

@endnode

@node ErSav "Saving a base"
@next ErSav
@toc Error

    @{b}@{fg highlight}Errors on saving, safe saving@{fg text}@{ub}

    Polyglot  saves  a base when you call '@{b}@{fg fill}Save@{ub}@{fg text}' from the main menu and also
when  you @{b}change a base@{ub} which you're working with and then want to @{b}delete@{ub} it
(by quitting or loading another base), it will ask you then.

    When you select the name of new file, it tries to open a dir (like while
@{" loading " link ErLoa}) and add the '@{b}@{fg fill}.plg@{ub}@{fg text}' extension if you forgot it.

    You  may  set  the  @{b}@{fg fill}Safe saving@{ub}@{fg text} option in the @{" prefs " link Prefs} window if you have
much space on disk or use a harddisk.
    It  works  only if you try to save a new file @{b}@{fg fill}over an existing@{ub}@{fg text} (with the
same  name),  e.g.   if  you  save a new version.  Normally, the old file is
@{b}removed@{ub} at once when you open the new one.  If there's a disk error, guru or
other  break,  you can't recover the old file and the new is incomplete.  It
happens rarely but it's better to insure.

    In the @{b}safe saving@{ub} mode, the program @{b}changes the name@{ub} of the old file to
'@{b}@{fg fill}_pol_temp.plg@{ub}@{fg text}'  and opens the @{b}new one@{ub}.  You need as much free space as both
files  take.  Else, you have to turn it off (or use another disk.  Hard disk
users may keep it on all time!).  It takes almost @{b}no additional time@{ub}.

    When  the  saving  is okay, the @{b}old file@{ub} is simply @{b}deleted@{ub}.  If an error
occurs, you may @{b}recover@{ub} the previous file or @{b}keep@{ub} the new incomplete one and
remove  the  old.   If  the  computer  turns  off or 'hangs' (not because of
Polyglot  of  course  :^)  during saving, a file called '@{b}@{fg fill}_pol_temp.plg@{ub}@{fg text}' will
remain  in  its  directory.   You may load it as a normal base and save with
other  name.   @{b}Warning:@{ub}  if you keep the @{b}@{fg fill}_pol_temp.plg@{ub}@{fg text} file, the safe saving
is @{b}impossible@{ub} in this directory!

@endnode


@node Histo "History and future"
@prev Error

    @{b}@{fg highlight}History@{fg text}@{ub}

    The  two first versions (1.0 and 1.1) has been @{b}never finished@{ub}, I changed
them  a  few times.  Mainly the user interface and service has been changing
then.  At now, the gadget service functions are really complex...
    The  main  application  of the program has been changing too (test types
mostly).    And   everything   started  from  an  idea  of  'another  little
word-tester'.  But the current version is the first finished release.

    @{b}@{fg fill}V1.2beta@{ub}@{fg text} - first finished version, many little errors, Polish only.

    @{b}@{fg fill}V1.21beta@{ub}@{fg text}  - first upgrade, but still beta.  Some small changes - better
lists   and  choose  test  service,  additional  frames  in  windows;  using
AFD-Copyright used and icons cleaned up.

    @{b}@{fg fill}V1.25@{ub}@{fg text}  -  the official release of Polyglot, available on Aminet; program
localized - English  and  Polish;  other  bugs  (e.g.   with string gadgets)
corrected.

    @{b}@{fg highlight}The future@{fg text}@{ub}

    At  present  I  don't think about extending the Polyglot, but who knows.
The  @{b}further future@{ub} of this and many other programs depends on @{b}your interest@{ub}
and @{b}shareware@{ub} donations.
    After the New Year I begin to write something new - it will be a big and
complex  file-operator.   It will be available (I hope) between May and June
1998.
    Well, and I have to go to school (yeah, maths-physics with computing and
those  pc...   :^(  and  perhaps a little bit of rational life ;^).  See the
next chapter about @{" ME " link Autho}.

@endnode

